:12pt; font-weight:bold">namely relationships.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">We believe that a focus on enhancing the relationships of the key stakeholders of schooling would have a dramatic impact on a school’s ability to improve standards of education</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Ofsted, and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">indeed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> schools and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">DfE, should ensure a g</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">reater focus on relational factors and should report regularly.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Relational Research is just beginning a three year project seeking to understand </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">school academic </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">success</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> by focusing on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">stakeholder relationships</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Schools involve a wide </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">range of internal and external stakeholders and there is a matrix of relationships in any school (and from school to school): these include students, teachers, support staff, educational specialists, administrators, governors, parents, local communities, f</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">aith communities (in some instances), local and central government and society at large.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Relational Research</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and Relationships Foundation </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">endeavour</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to influence public policy and organisational pr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">actice with a relational agenda</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The aim is to build ‘relati</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">onal capital’ in the lives of families and communities through the way organisations and structures are</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">arranged</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, and through the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> goals they set for themselves.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We want </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to understand the means by which relational practice can be fostered in schools. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We wish to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">determine ways in which schools and students can be assessed for their relational understanding and competence.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We are interested in the ways in which the interconnection of key stakeholders intersect at critical stages in a student’s school ca</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">reer, establishing ways of evaluating how such impact is manifested, with a view to transferring emergent understanding to other students, and to thus support successful outcomes.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> We provide practical help to schools to intervene and encourage greater prox</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">imity between the key stakeholders in education and thus improve student outcomes. We have worked </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">successfully i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">various</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">public service settings such as primary health care and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">prisons</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Chief Inspector of Ofsted, Sir Michael Wilshaw, makes several recommendations in response to issues and concerns raised in the Annual Report relating </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to the performance of schools; w</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e would like to highlight a neglected element. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In a recent session </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">committee</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the chair, Graham Stuart MP, highlighted this fundamental neglected element with Sir Michael Wi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">shaw asking specific questions on the subject of “</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">quality relationships</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">” which in his words need addressing. He stated, “</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Every time we look at chi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ldren struggling in this country, it’s the quality of relationships with adults which comes back again and again as the thing they’re craving. What is there around organisations and fermenting and supporting these organisations which could lead to the comm</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">unity coming back again?</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">” Mr Stuart’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">interest</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is one we share: wishing for people to be good citizens it is not enough; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">we are going to have to find some kind of policy approach to facilitate more high quality relationships between adults and children</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.”</span></p><p style="font-size:6pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:6pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Strengthening relationships in the home and school</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The most critical need </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is the problems</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> created by poor or dysfunctional relationships which leads to low levels of motivation and achievement of pupils in schools, and conflict and/or loneliness among communities, families and individuals across society (which we refer to as ‘relational povert</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">y’). The correlation between relational breakdown in the home and poor educational outcomes is well documented. Parents from such backgrounds are often</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">but not exclusively</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in housing and community contexts which make it hard for positive relationships to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> be sustained</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">E</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">vidence from Feinstein and Symons suggests that parental involvement with education </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(which is defined here as the amount of time and quality of an interaction with a child rather than traditional measures of engagement such as attendance a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t parent/consultation evenings or participation in committees) is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the, ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">single greatest predictor of achievement</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic; vertical-align:super">’</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and most importantly</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> factors such as the educational experience of a parent or the socio-economic context of the home </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">can be</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> counterbalanced by strong productive relationships. True parental engagement is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(perhaps) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">not with the school but with the child. Supporting and intervening in this relationship is considered vital.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Evidence from those like Bergin and Bergin </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(2009) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">demon</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">strate that students</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> who develop positive relationships with teachers </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">achieve stronger academic outcomes.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Where strong relationships are fostered between teachers and students, evidence suggests that poor or dysfunctional relationships in the home can be p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">artially compensated for</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Conversely, r</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">esearch by the Centre for Social Justice </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(2000) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">suggests that over two-thirds of all those who truanted did so in order to avoid a particular lesson, with ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">relationship with the teacher</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’ cited as one of the principal</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> grounds for relational breakdown.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Where relationships are strong in the classroom, they can </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">surmount </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">social inequality; where they are poor or dysfunctional, evidence suggests they reinforce educational disadvantage.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Positive peer to peer relationships a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">lso impact on student’s academic and non-academic functioning in secondary education. Positive peer interaction correlates well with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">student</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> motivation (Furrer and Skinner, 2003), </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">student</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> engagement (Keefe and Berndt, 1996) and academic </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">outcomes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (Keefe and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Berndt, 1995).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Policy </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.1</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Schools should be supported to provide more robust assessment of the relationships that sustain their performance.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Ofsted should review the extent to which schools are able to effectively evaluate </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">relationships and identify means of improving them.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Given the importance of relationships for the provision of schooling (and other policy outcomes) the Department for Education should report on the extent to which it sees relationships as a limiting </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">factor in school improvement and how such relationships might be improved.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'FS Me'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'FS Me'; font-size:8pt"> Feinstein, L. &amp; Symons, J. (1999). Attainment in secondary school. Oxford Economic Papers, 51, 300-321.</span></p></body></html>